AS400 supplies only its business data. It does not need to provide timestamps, UUIDs, correlation IDs, or payload versions.

## 3. `007-as400-user-import.yaml`

```yaml
databaseChangeLog:

  # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
  # 1. Create a temporary staging table
  # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
  - changeSet:
      id: 007-01-create-as400-user-staging
      author: partner-repository

      preConditions:
        onFail: MARK_RAN
        not:
          tableExists:
            tableName: as400_user_import_staging

      changes:
        - createTable:
            tableName: as400_user_import_staging
            columns:
              - column:
                  name: entity
                  type: varchar(50)

              - column:
                  name: source_record_type
                  type: varchar(50)

              - column:
                  name: related_parent
                  type: varchar(100)

              - column:
                  name: source_personal_id
                  type: varchar(100)

              - column:
                  name: gps_group_number
                  type: varchar(100)

              - column:
                  name: source_point_of_sales_id
                  type: varchar(100)

              - column:
                  name: first_name
                  type: varchar(100)

              - column:
                  name: surname
                  type: varchar(100)

              - column:
                  name: email
                  type: varchar(255)

              - column:
                  name: phone_number
                  type: varchar(50)

              - column:
                  name: language
                  type: varchar(10)

              - column:
                  name: user_status
                  type: varchar(20)

              - column:
                  name: sales_point_id
                  type: varchar(100)

              - column:
                  name: sales_point_name
                  type: varchar(255)

              - column:
                  name: relationship_type
                  type: varchar(50)

              - column:
                  name: relationship_status
                  type: varchar(20)

              - column:
                  name: imported_at
                  type: timestamp with time zone
                  defaultValueComputed: CURRENT_TIMESTAMP

      rollback:
        - dropTable:
            tableName: as400_user_import_staging


  # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
  # 2. Clear the staging table before loading the controlled CSV
  # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
  - changeSet:
      id: 007-02-clear-as400-user-staging
      author: partner-repository

      changes:
        - delete:
            tableName: as400_user_import_staging


  # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
  # 3. Load the CSV into the staging table
  # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
  - changeSet:
      id: 007-03-load-as400-user-csv
      author: partner-repository

      changes:
        - loadData:
            file: ../data/as400-users.csv
            relativeToChangelogFile: true
            tableName: as400_user_import_staging
            encoding: UTF-8
            separator: ","
            quotchar: '"'
            usePreparedStatements: true

            columns:
              - column:
                  header: entity
                  name: entity
                  type: STRING

              - column:
                  header: source_record_type
                  name: source_record_type
                  type: STRING

              - column:
                  header: related_parent
                  name: related_parent
                  type: STRING

              - column:
                  header: source_personal_id
                  name: source_personal_id
                  type: STRING

              - column:
                  header: gps_group_number
                  name: gps_group_number
                  type: STRING

              - column:
                  header: source_point_of_sales_id
                  name: source_point_of_sales_id
                  type: STRING

              - column:
                  header: first_name
                  name: first_name
                  type: STRING

              - column:
                  header: surname
                  name: surname
                  type: STRING

              - column:
                  header: email
                  name: email
                  type: STRING

              - column:
                  header: phone_number
                  name: phone_number
                  type: STRING

              - column:
                  header: language
                  name: language
                  type: STRING

              - column:
                  header: user_status
                  name: user_status
                  type: STRING

              - column:
                  header: sales_point_id
                  name: sales_point_id
                  type: STRING

              - column:
                  header: sales_point_name
                  name: sales_point_name
                  type: STRING

              - column:
                  header: relationship_type
                  name: relationship_type
                  type: STRING

              - column:
                  header: relationship_status
                  name: relationship_status
                  type: STRING


  # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
  # 4. Insert or update users
  #
  # Change table/column names to match your actual user table.
  # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
  - changeSet:
      id: 007-04-upsert-users
      author: partner-repository
      dbms: postgresql

      changes:
        - sql:
            sql: |
              INSERT INTO users (
                  user_id,
                  username,
                  gps_group_number,
                  source_personal_id,
                  entity,
                  first_name,
                  last_name,
                  email,
                  phone_number,
                  language,
                  status,
                  created_at,
                  updated_at
              )
              SELECT DISTINCT ON (BTRIM(gps_group_number))
                  BTRIM(gps_group_number) AS user_id,
                  BTRIM(gps_group_number) AS username,
                  BTRIM(gps_group_number) AS gps_group_number,
                  BTRIM(source_personal_id) AS source_personal_id,
                  BTRIM(entity) AS entity,
                  BTRIM(first_name) AS first_name,
                  BTRIM(surname) AS last_name,
                  NULLIF(BTRIM(email), '') AS email,
                  NULLIF(BTRIM(phone_number), '') AS phone_number,
                  NULLIF(BTRIM(language), '') AS language,
                  BTRIM(user_status) AS status,
                  CURRENT_TIMESTAMP AS created_at,
                  CURRENT_TIMESTAMP AS updated_at
              FROM as400_user_import_staging
              WHERE gps_group_number IS NOT NULL
                AND BTRIM(gps_group_number) <> ''
              ORDER BY BTRIM(gps_group_number), imported_at DESC

              ON CONFLICT (user_id)
              DO UPDATE SET
                  username = EXCLUDED.username,
                  gps_group_number = EXCLUDED.gps_group_number,
                  source_personal_id = EXCLUDED.source_personal_id,
                  entity = EXCLUDED.entity,
                  first_name = EXCLUDED.first_name,
                  last_name = EXCLUDED.last_name,
                  email = EXCLUDED.email,
                  phone_number = EXCLUDED.phone_number,
                  language = EXCLUDED.language,
                  status = EXCLUDED.status,
                  updated_at = CURRENT_TIMESTAMP;


  # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
  # 5. Insert or update sales points
  # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
  - changeSet:
      id: 007-05-upsert-sales-points
      author: partner-repository
      dbms: postgresql

      changes:
        - sql:
            sql: |
              INSERT INTO sales_point (
                  sales_point_id,
                  label,
                  created_at,
                  updated_at
              )
              SELECT DISTINCT ON (BTRIM(sales_point_id))
                  BTRIM(sales_point_id) AS sales_point_id,
                  BTRIM(sales_point_name) AS label,
                  CURRENT_TIMESTAMP AS created_at,
                  CURRENT_TIMESTAMP AS updated_at
              FROM as400_user_import_staging
              WHERE sales_point_id IS NOT NULL
                AND BTRIM(sales_point_id) <> ''
              ORDER BY BTRIM(sales_point_id), imported_at DESC

              ON CONFLICT (sales_point_id)
              DO UPDATE SET
                  label = EXCLUDED.label,
                  updated_at = CURRENT_TIMESTAMP;


  # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
  # 6. Insert or update user-sales-point relationships
  # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
  - changeSet:
      id: 007-06-upsert-user-sales-point-relationships
      author: partner-repository
      dbms: postgresql

      changes:
        - sql:
            sql: |
              INSERT INTO person_sales_point_relationship (
                  person_user_id,
                  sales_point_id,
                  relationship_type,
                  org_unit_id,
                  status,
                  created_at,
                  updated_at
              )
              SELECT DISTINCT
                  BTRIM(gps_group_number) AS person_user_id,
                  BTRIM(sales_point_id) AS sales_point_id,
                  BTRIM(relationship_type) AS relationship_type,
                  COALESCE(
                      NULLIF(BTRIM(source_point_of_sales_id), ''),
                      BTRIM(sales_point_id)
                  ) AS org_unit_id,
                  BTRIM(relationship_status) AS status,
                  CURRENT_TIMESTAMP AS created_at,
                  CURRENT_TIMESTAMP AS updated_at
              FROM as400_user_import_staging
              WHERE gps_group_number IS NOT NULL
                AND BTRIM(gps_group_number) <> ''
                AND sales_point_id IS NOT NULL
                AND BTRIM(sales_point_id) <> ''
                AND relationship_type IS NOT NULL
                AND BTRIM(relationship_type) <> ''

              ON CONFLICT (
                  person_user_id,
                  sales_point_id,
                  relationship_type
              )
              DO UPDATE SET
                  org_unit_id = EXCLUDED.org_unit_id,
                  status = EXCLUDED.status,
                  updated_at = CURRENT_TIMESTAMP;


  # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
  # 7. Clear staging after a successful import
  # ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
  - changeSet:
      id: 007-07-clear-staging-after-import
      author: partner-repository

      changes:
        - delete:
            tableName: as400_user_import_staging
```

## 4. Relationship unique constraint

The relationship upsert needs a unique constraint covering:

```text
person_user_id + sales_point_id + relationship_type
```

Add this before the import changeset, unless it already exists:

```yaml
databaseChangeLog:
  - changeSet:
      id: 006-add-relationship-unique-constraint
      author: partner-repository

      preConditions:
        onFail: MARK_RAN
        not:
          uniqueConstraintExists:
            tableName: person_sales_point_relationship
            constraintName: uk_person_sales_point_relationship

      changes:
        - addUniqueConstraint:
            tableName: person_sales_point_relationship
            columnNames: person_user_id, sales_point_id, relationship_type
            constraintName: uk_person_sales_point_relationship
```

Then update `master.yaml`:

```yaml
databaseChangeLog:
  - include:
      file: changes/006-relationship-unique-constraint.yaml
      relativeToChangelogFile: true

  - include:
      file: changes/007-as400-user-import.yaml
      relativeToChangelogFile: true
```

## Check these names before running

The example assumes:

```text
users
sales_point
person_sales_point_relationship
```

It also assumes all three tables have:

```text
created_at
updated_at
```

Remove those columns from the SQL when your actual tables do not have them.

The user table must have a unique or primary-key constraint on:

```text
user_id
```

The sales-point table must have a unique or primary-key constraint on:

```text
sales_point_id
```

This import writes directly to PostgreSQL. It does not execute your Java `PingUserClient`, so Ping provisioning remains a separate step.

